      "section": "Lede",
      "content": "The UK government faces a critical test in its post-Brexit immigration plans as it aims to process 3.5 million EU citizens’ applications for 'settled status' by 2021, but doubts about the feasibility of the timeline and staffing targets have emerged. Despite Immigration Minister Brandon Lewis’s assurances of a smooth rollout, analysts and critics argue unresolved issues—such as the role of the European Court of Justice (ECJ) and bureaucratic hurdles—cast doubt on the claims."
    },
    {
      "section": "Process and Recruitment",
      "content": "Lewis told the Commons Home Affairs Select Committee that the government will recruit an additional 1,200 staff (700 already on board), primarily in the UK Visas and Immigration (UKVI) agency, which currently processes 3 million visa applications annually with 6,500 staff. Home Affairs Committee Chair Yvette Cooper expressed skepticism, citing the three-month delay in processing temporary permanent residence documents and questioning if 1,200 is enough to handle 3.5 million applications in two years."
    },
    {
      "section": "Negotiation Hopes and Stickpoints",
      "content": "Lewis remained optimistic an agreement could be reached with the EU by Christmas 2019 but declined to comment on leaks suggesting the ECJ might play a role in a two-year transition period. The 3million group representing EU nationals criticized this as "stumbling blocks" due to continued differences over ECJ jurisdiction, family reunification rights affecting thousands, and protection from 'hostile environment measures.'"
    },
    {
      "section": "Current Delays and Stances",
      "content": "Applications for pre-Brexit permanent residence have a three-month backlog. The government’s position on non-EU nationals denied settled status includes freezing bank accounts and potential deportation before court appeal, a measure opposition MPs like Yvette Cooper warn could exacerbate uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "section": "Conclusion",
      "content": "With 3million EU nationals awaiting status, the government’s promises hinge on resolving ECJ-related ambiguities and scaling staffing effectively. Critics argue the current trajectory risks jeopardizing the rights of millions, especially without a clear deal by Christmas."
    }
  ]
